        "en": [
          "Located at the gates of the Cevennes, the village of Saint Jean de Valériscle is still impregnated with its recent mining past. This village is remarkable for its preserved medieval houses. They form the ramparts by their entanglement and their communicating cellars. The narrow streets and vaulted passages lead to a small square on which the Romanesque church and the 13th century castle are located. The Barry district retains a striking medieval atmosphere and bears witness to an original circular urbanism called \"circulade\".\n\nTo see:\n- The Romanesque church, destroyed during the wars of religion, restored in the 17th and 19th centuries.\n- The Château du Barry (private), dating from the 13th century, having served as housing for miners.\n- The museum of coats of arms, more than 600 coats of arms are presented in 7 rooms, as well as collections of weapons and costumes.\n- The remains of the railway branch line, used to transport the coal extracted from the mines, further up the valley.\n-\tThe paths and forest tracks leading to the Chapel of N.D des Oliviers, the remains of the Castle of Maricon, the cross of Mortisson."
